2026-06-10 16:20:46,098 DEBUG Tool result: ToolCallRecord(
    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_26dcb211377b48cab54b69d6',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt": "Retrieve information about capital expenditures, capital intensity, depreciation relative to capex, and asset-heavy investments by segment from {{spaceX_s1}}, including any disclosures about satellite constellation costs, data center investments, launch vehicle development, and property/equipment levels."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'Retrieve information about capital expenditures, capital intensity, depreciation relative to capex, and asset-heavy investments by segment from {{spaceX_s1}}, including any disclosures about satellite constellation costs, data center investments, launch vehicle development, and property/equipment levels.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Capital Expenditures, Capital Intensity, Depreciation & Asset-Heavy Investments by Segment\n\n## 1. Capital Expenditures by Segment\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Period | Space | Connectivity | AI | **Total** |\n|--------|------:|-------------:|---:|----------:|\n| **Q1 2026** | $1,052M | $1,332M | $7,723M | **$10,107M** |\n| **Q1 2025** | $759M | $814M | $2,567M | **$4,140M** |\n| **FY 2025** | $3,832M | $4,178M | $12,727M | **$20,737M** |\n| **FY 2024** | $2,032M | $3,498M | $5,633M | **$11,163M** |\n| **FY 2023** | $1,497M | $2,455M | $463M | **$4,415M** |\n\n### Year-over-Year Growth Rates\n\n| Segment | FY 2024 → FY 2025 | FY 2023 → FY 2024 | Q1 2025 → Q1 2026 |\n|---------|-------------------:|-------------------:|-------------------:|\n| Space | +89% ($1,800M) | +36% ($535M) | +39% ($293M) |\n| Connectivity | +19% ($680M) | +42% ($1,043M) | +64% ($518M) |\n| AI | +126% ($7,094M) | +1,116% ($5,170M) | +201% ($5,156M) |\n| **Total** | **+86% ($9,574M)** | **+153% ($6,748M)** | **+144% ($5,967M)** |\n\n### Key Observations\n\n- **AI segment dominates capex**, accounting for **76%** of total Q1 2026 capex ($7,723M of $10,107M) and **61%** of FY 2025 capex ($12,727M of $20,737M).\n- **AI capex grew from $463M in 2023 to $12,727M in 2025** — a **27.5× increase** in two years — driven by rapid terrestrial data center expansion.\n- **Connectivity capex** grew steadily, driven by satellite and ground equipment for Starlink constellation expansion.\n- **Space capex** nearly doubled in FY 2025, driven by Starship launch site infrastructure.\n- **Q1 2026 total capex of $10.1B** annualizes to ~$40.4B, suggesting continued acceleration.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Capital Intensity (Capex / Revenue)\n\n### Approximate Capital Intensity Ratios\n\n| Period | Total Capex | Total Revenue (est.) | **Capex / Revenue** |\n|--------|------------:|---------------------:|--------------------:|\n| **FY 2023** | $4,415M | $10,387M | **42.5%** |\n| **FY 2024** | $11,163M | $14,015M | **79.6%** |\n| **FY 2025** | $20,737M | ~$18,674M* | **~111%** |\n\n*\\*FY 2025 revenue estimated from segment disclosures: Space ~$4,086M, Connectivity $11,387M, AI $3,201M.*\n\n### Segment-Level Capital Intensity (FY 2024)\n\n| Segment | Capex | Revenue | Capex / Revenue |\n|---------|------:|--------:|----------------:|\n| Space | $2,032M | $3,796M | **53.5%** |\n| Connectivity | $3,498M | $7,599M | **46.0%** |\n| AI | $5,633M | $2,620M | **215.0%** |\n\n### Key Observations\n\n- **Total capital intensity surpassed 100% in FY 2025**, meaning the company invested more in capex than it generated in revenue — an extraordinary level driven almost entirely by the AI segment.\n- **AI capital intensity exceeded 200%** in FY 2024 ($5,633M capex vs. $2,620M revenue), reflecting the company\'s stated strategy of "prioritiz[ing] growth and investment to capture significant opportunities in AI applications and compute infrastructure" at the expense of near-term profitability.\n- **Connectivity capital intensity** remained relatively stable (~46%), reflecting disciplined expansion of the Starlink constellation alongside strong revenue growth.\n- The company explicitly warns: *"We may choose to increase or accelerate the pace of any of these investments at any time, which could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."*\n\n---\n\n## 3. Depreciation Relative to Capital Expenditures\n\n### Consolidated Depreciation vs. Capex\n\n| Period | Depreciation | Capex | **Depreciation / Capex** | **Capex / Depreciation** |\n|--------|-------------:|------:|-------------------------:|-------------------------:|\n| **FY 2023** | $2,635M | $4,415M | **59.7%** | 1.68× |\n| **FY 2024** | $2,977M | $11,163M | **26.7%** | 3.75× |\n| **FY 2025** | $5,915M | $20,737M | **28.5%** | 3.51× |\n| **Q1 2025** | $1,237M | $4,140M | **29.9%** | 3.35× |\n| **Q1 2026** | $2,329M | $10,107M | **23.0%** | 4.34× |\n\n### Segment-Level Depreciation (FY 2024 Supplemental Data)\n\n| Segment | Depreciation & Amortization | Capex | **D&A / Capex** |\n|---------|----------------------------:|------:|----------------:|\n| Space | $637M | $2,032M | **31.3%** |\n| Connectivity | $1,508M | $3,498M | **43.1%** |\n| AI | $1,679M | $5,633M | **29.8%** |\n| **Total** | **$3,824M** | **$11,163M** | **34.3%** |\n\n### Segment-Level Depreciation (FY 2023)\n\n| Segment | Depreciation & Amortization | Capex | **D&A / Capex** |\n|---------|----------------------------:|------:|----------------:|\n| Space | $571M | $1,497M | **38.1%** |\n| Connectivity | $884M | $2,455M | **36.0%** |\n| AI | $1,180M | $463M | **254.9%** |\n| **Total** | **$2,635M** | **$4,415M** | **59.7%** |\n\n### Key Observations\n\n- The **depreciation-to-capex ratio has collapsed from ~60% in 2023 to ~23% in Q1 2026**, indicating that the company is investing at a pace far exceeding the amortization of its existing asset base. This is characteristic of a company in an aggressive capital formation phase.\n- For every $1 of depreciation, the company is now investing **$4.34** in new capex (Q1 2026), up from $1.68× in FY 2023.\n- **AI segment D&A was 255% of capex in FY 2023** because the segment had significant existing assets (from the xAI acquisition) being depreciated while capex was still modest ($463M). By FY 2024, as data center buildout accelerated, the ratio normalized to ~30%.\n- **Connectivity has the highest D&A/capex ratio** among segments (~43%), consistent with a maturing satellite fleet with established depreciation schedules being supplemented by incremental constellation growth.\n- The **rapid growth in depreciation** ($2,635M in 2023 → $5,915M in 2025) reflects the massive new asset base being placed into service, particularly GPU servers and satellites.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Property, Plant & Equipment Composition\n\n### Consolidated PP&E (Gross)\n\n| Asset Category | March 31, 2026 | Dec 31, 2025 | Dec 31, 2024 | YoY Change (2024→2025) |\n|---------------|---------------:|-------------:|-------------:|-----------------------:|\n| **Servers & networking equipment** | $23,850M | $22,694M | $6,892M | **+230%** |\n| **Satellites** | $12,893M | $11,949M | $7,591M | **+57%** |\n| Machinery & equipment | $8,020M | $6,343M | $5,343M | +19% |\n| **Data center infrastructure** | $2,965M | $2,960M | $224M | **+1,221%** |\n| Launch sites | $2,479M | $2,404M | $2,121M | +13% |\n| Land, buildings & improvements | $2,018M | $1,876M | $913M | +105% |\n| Flight vehicle hardware | $1,459M | $1,689M | $1,577M | +7% |\n| Leasehold improvements | $842M | $784M | $1,019M | −23% |\n| **Construction-in-progress** | **$14,045M** | **$4,604M** | **$3,007M** | **+53%** |\n| **Total Gross PP&E** | **$68,571M** | **$55,303M** | **$28,687M** | **+93%** |\n| Less: Accumulated depreciation | ($14,692M) | ($12,701M) | ($7,540M) | +68% |\n| **Net PP&E** | **$53,879M** | **$42,602M** | **$21,147M** | **+101%** |\n\n### Key Observations\n\n- **Net PP&E more than doubled** from $21.1B (Dec 2024) to $42.6B (Dec 2025), and reached $53.9B by March 31, 2026.\n- **Servers & networking equipment** surged from $6.9B to $22.7B (+230%) in 2025, representing the largest single asset category — driven almost entirely by AI GPU and server deployments.\n- **Construction-in-progress exploded from $4.6B to $14.0B in a single quarter** (Q1 2026), indicating massive ongoing data center and infrastructure construction not yet placed into service.\n- **Data center infrastructure** grew from $224M to $2,960M (+1,221%), reflecting the formal recognition of completed AI data center facilities.\n- **Satellites** grew 57% to $11.9B, reflecting continued Starlink constellation expansion.\n- **Accumulated depreciation** was $12.7B on a $55.3B gross base (Dec 2025), yielding an **average remaining useful life ratio of ~77%** — indicating a relatively young asset base overall.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Asset-Heavy Investment Drivers by Segment\n\n### 🚀 Space Segment\n\n| Metric | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Trend |\n|--------|--------:|--------:|--------:|-------|\n| Capex | $1,497M | $2,032M | $3,832M | ↑↑ |\n| D&A | $571M | $637M | N/A | ↑ |\n\n**Primary investment drivers:**\n- **Starship vehicle development**: The company describes Starship as its "next-generation vehicle" that will "dramatically expand launch capability through full and rapid reusability combined with unprecedented mass to orbit capability." Expected to carry 100 metric tons (V3) to potentially 200 metric tons (V4).\n- **Launch site infrastructure**: Increased investment in launch facilities to support Starship, driving the $293M Q1 2026 increase.\n- **R&D acceleration**: Space R&D increased $404M in Q1 2026 (+$1,169M in FY 2025) "driven by accelerated investment in our Starship vehicle and related facilities."\n- **Cost reduction thesis**: SpaceX believes Starship "can eventually reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more relative to the historical average launch cost per kilogram according to NASA of $18,500."\n- **Impairments**: $24M in FY 2024 and $24M in Q1 2025 for damaged flight vehicles.\n- **Flight vehicle hardware** actually *decreased* from $1,689M to $1,459M in Q1 2026, suggesting vehicle retirements/use exceeded new builds.\n\n### 🛰️ Connectivity Segment (Starlink)\n\n| Metric | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Trend |\n|--------|--------:|--------:|--------:|-------|\n| Capex | $2,455M | $3,498M | $4,178M | ↑ |\n| D&A | $884M | $1,508M | N/A | ↑↑ |\n\n**Primary investment drivers:**\n- **Satellite constellation expansion**: Satellites on the balance sheet grew from $7.6B to $11.9B (+57%) in 2025, reflecting thousands of new Starlink satellites placed into orbit.\n- **Ground equipment**: Higher satellite and ground equipment costs "as we continue to increase our number of satellites and grow our satellite network."\n- **Satellite cost capitalization**: Per the accounting policy, satellite costs include "costs to build the 