        output='\n## Two Situations Where EBITDA-Based Segment Comparations Materially Misrepresent Economic Profitability\n\n### Background: The Filing\'s Non-GAAP Framework\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as segment income (loss) from operations **plus** depreciation & amortization, share-based compensation, restructuring charges, and impairment. Management presents it as "a meaningful performance measure for investors to evaluate our operating performance and to compare the financial results" across its three segments (Space, Connectivity, and AI). The filing explicitly warns that "other companies may calculate Adjusted EBITDA or similarly titled measures differently."\n\nGiven that the filing simultaneously emphasizes Segment Adjusted EBITDA **and** discloses extraordinary capital intensity (total capex of $20.7B in FY 2025 exceeded total revenue of $18.7B, and the D&A-to-capex ratio collapsed from ~60% in 2023 to ~23% in Q1 2026), two specific situations arise in which EBITDA-based segment comparisons could materially misrepresent economic profitability:\n\n---\n\n### Situation 1: Massive Capex-to-Depreciation Gap Distorts EBITDA as a Cash-Earnings Proxy Across Segments with Varying Investment Phases\n\n**The core problem:** EBITDA adds back all depreciation & amortization, implicitly assuming that D&A is a reliable proxy for the capital reinvestment required to sustain current operations. When capex vastly exceeds D&A—and does so unevenly across segments—EBITDA systematically overstates sustainable cash generation for segments in aggressive investment phases and understates it for segments with more mature capital cycles.\n\n**Quantitative evidence from the filing:**\n\n| Metric | Space | Connectivity | AI | Total |\n|--------|------:|-------------:|---:|------:|\n| **FY 2025 Capex** | $3,832M | $4,178M | $12,727M | $20,737M |\n| **FY 2025 D&A** | ~$757M | ~$2,376M | ~$3,568M | ~$6,701M |\n| **Capex / D&A** | ~5.1× | ~1.8× | ~3.6× | ~3.1× |\n| **FY 2025 Segment Adj. EBITDA** | $653M | $7,168M | $(1,237)M | $6,584M |\n\nThe consolidated D&A-to-capex ratio declined from **59.7% in FY 2023** to **23.0% in Q1 2026**, meaning the company is now investing **$4.34 in new capital for every $1 of depreciation recorded**. Construction-in-progress alone surged from $4.6B (Dec 2025) to $14.0B (Q1 2026), indicating that enormous volumes of capital are being deployed but have not yet begun generating revenue or depreciation.\n\n**How this distorts segment comparisons:**\n\n- **Connectivity** appears to be the overwhelming earnings engine at $7,168M Segment Adjusted EBITDA. However, the segment required $4,178M in capex (primarily satellite constellation expansion) to sustain and grow its revenue base. Capital intensity is ~36.7% of segment revenue ($4,178M / $11,387M). The D&A/capex ratio of ~57% is the highest among segments, indicating a more mature asset cycle. EBITDA therefore **modestly overstates** sustainable cash earnings but remains a reasonable directional indicator.\n\n- **AI** shows a Segment Adjusted EBITDA loss of $(1,237)M, which an investor might view as a manageable operating shortfall. In reality, the segment consumed **$12,727M in capex**—more than 10× its EBITDA loss and nearly 4× its revenue of $3,201M. The true economic deficit (capex minus Segment Adjusted EBITDA) was approximately **$13,964M**. EBITDA completely masks the magnitude of capital destruction occurring in this segment. Net PP&E for the consolidated entity more than doubled from $21.1B to $42.6B in a single year, driven overwhelmingly by AI data center buildout (servers & networking equipment grew +230% YoY).\n\n- **Space** appears modestly profitable at $653M Segment Adjusted EBITDA for FY 2025, but consumed $3,832M in capex (driven by Starship development and launch infrastructure), producing a capex/D&A ratio of ~5.1×. The segment\'s capex-to-revenue ratio was ~93.8%. EBITDA-based reporting suggests the segment generates meaningful positive cash flow, when in economic terms the segment consumed roughly $3,179M more in capital than its EBITDA generated.\n\n**The misrepresentation:** Comparing Connectivity\'s $7,168M EBITDA to Space\'s $653M and AI\'s $(1,237)M creates the impression of a single high-performing segment funding two modestly-sized problem areas. The capital-consumption reality is starkly different: Connectivity required $4.2B, Space required $3.8B, and AI required $12.7B in capex—meaning **AI\'s true capital appetite is 3× that of the profitable segment** while generating negative EBITDA. EBITDA-based comparisons understate the scale of cross-subsidization from Connectivity to the other two segments.\n\n---\n\n### Situation 2: Non-Uniform Capital Structures and Off-Balance-Sheet Obligations Create Comparability Distortions Across Segments with Different Asset Bases\n\n**The core problem:** EBITDA excludes interest expense, taxes, depreciation, and amortization, which means it is completely silent on how each segment\'s operations are financed and the associated cost of capital. When segments have materially different capital structures—mixes of owned vs. leased assets, varying debt-to-asset ratios, or different financing arrangements—EBITDA-based comparisons treat identically-EBITDA segments as equally profitable regardless of their vastly different claims on capital.\n\n**Evidence from the filing:**\n\n1. **Operating vs. Finance Leases:** The filing discloses $1,558M in operating lease liabilities and $1,237M in finance lease liabilities as of December 31, 2025. Operating lease expense totaled $848M and finance lease expense totaled $647M (including $317M in interest) for FY 2025. The finance lease interest of $317M is excluded from EBITDA, yet it represents a real, contractually obligated cost of capital. The weighted-average discount rate on finance leases is **22.6%**, indicating high-cost financing arrangements—likely concentrated in the GPU-heavy AI segment. Two segments with identical EBITDA but different finance lease profiles would have materially different free cash flow generation.\n\n2. **Capitalized Interest and Segment-Specific Financing:** The filing discloses $169M in capitalized interest in FY 2025 and $7M in Q1 2026, exclusively tied to AI data center construction. This capitalized interest is embedded in the asset base and flows through depreciation over time, but the **cash cost of borrowing** to fund AI capex is a real economic charge that EBITDA ignores. The filing notes that AI investments were funded "substantially through debt ($16B+ in new financing for AI in FY 2025)" and equity ($7.4B from stock sales in Q1 2026). The cost of this financing does not appear in Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n3. **Asset Age and Useful Life Heterogeneity:** The filing reveals that average remaining useful life across the consolidated asset base is ~77% (accumulated depreciation of $12.7B on a $55.3B gross base). However, this masks dramatic differences: the Connectivity segment\'s satellite fleet is more mature (satellite D&A/capex ratio of ~57%), while AI\'s server fleet is overwhelmingly new (servers & networking equipment grew +230% in one year, with accumulated depreciation still a small fraction of gross cost). The filing also notes that a one-year change in estimated satellite useful life would impact operating income by **$480M**—indicating significant management judgment in depreciation estimates that EBITDA entirely bypasses.\n\n**How this distorts segment comparisons:**\n\n- The AI segment\'s Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $(1,237)M excludes not only $3,568M in D&A but also a disproportionate share of the $317M in finance lease interest and a substantial portion of the $169M in capitalized interest, all of which are economically tied to its data center buildout. Two segments could show identical EBITDA but one could be entirely equity-financed with long-lived assets while the other is debt-financed with short-lived assets requiring continuous reinvestment—and EBITDA would be completely blind to this difference.\n\n- The Connectivity segment benefits from a relatively stable capital structure (satellites with 5-year depreciation schedules deployed and generating revenue), while the AI segment\'s $14.0B in construction-in-progress represents assets that are neither generating revenue nor being depreciated. EBITDA comparisons treat the two segments\' current operating performance as directly comparable, but Connectivity\'s EBITDA is backed by a productive, revenue-generating asset base while AI\'s negative EBITDA sits atop an enormous, largely pre-revenue capital base with carrying costs that EBITDA does not capture.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Situation | EBITDA Distortion | Filing-Specific Evidence | Impact on Segment Comparability |\n|-----------|-------------------|--------------------------|-------------------------------|\n| **1. Capex/D&A Gap** | EBITDA overstates sustainable cash generation when capex vastly exceeds D&A, as it excludes the capital expenditure required to maintain/grow the asset base | D&A/capex collapsed from 60% (2023) to 23% (Q1 2026); AI capex was 3.6× D&A while AI EBITDA was $(1,237)M; CIP surged to $14.0B | Connectivity appears to "fund" modest shortfalls elsewhere, when in reality AI consumed 3× more capital than Connectivity; Space\'s modest $653M EBITDA masked $3,832M capex |\n| **2. Capital Structure & Off-Balance-Sheet Heterogeneity** | EBITDA is silent on financing costs, lease structures, asset age profiles, and capitalized interest—creating false comparability | Finance lease interest of $317M at 22.6% rate; $169M capitalized interest (AI only); $16B+ new debt financing (AI); satellite useful-life sensitivity of $480M per year | Two segments with identical EBITDA could have dramatically different free cash flows and returns on capital depending on how their operations are financed and how capital-intensive their asset renewal cycles are |\n\n**Bottom line:** When a company presents Segment Adjusted EBITDA as its primary performance metric while simultaneously operating in a regime where capex runs at 111% of revenue and varies from 37% (Connectivity) to 397% (AI) of segment revenue, EBITDA ceases to be a meaningful proxy for economic profitability. The add-back of D&A—representing only $6.7B of the $20.7B in annual capital consumption—obscures the true cost of maintaining and growing the enterprise\'s capital base, particularly for investors attempting to compare capital-light and capital-heavy segments on a like-for-like basis.\n',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=True,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=0.0,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
